Hi,

we experiencing weird issue with changing password in our MVC Web App.
The error "Optimistic concurrency failure, object has been modified" occurs when we try change password with ChangePasswordAsync method.

This is the code in controller:
```
[HttpPost]
        [ActionName("ChangePassword")]
        [ValidateAntiForgeryToken]
        public async Task<IActionResult> ChangePasswordPost()
        {
            var viewModel = await BindViewModel<ChangePasswordViewModel>();

            if (ModelState.IsValid)
            {
                var user = await _userManagerStore.FindByNameAsync(User.Identity.Name);
                var result = await _userManagerStore.ChangePasswordAsync(user, viewModel.CurrentPassword, viewModel.NewPassword);
                if (result.Succeeded)
                {
                    // log success and redirect to index
return RedirectToAction("Index", "Home");
                }

                foreach (var error in result.Errors)
                {
                    ModelState.AddModelError(string.Empty, error.Description);
                }
            }

            return View(viewModel);
        }
```
It fails on the error i describe above at this line:
`var result = await _userManagerStore.ChangePasswordAsync(user, viewModel.CurrentPassword, viewModel.NewPassword);`

But after that, when i log out from app, i can login again with the old password (so the password didn't changed). And when try change password again, it says "Incorrect password".

I want to run Kestrel on Ubuntu with https and do:

```options.Listen(IPAddress.Any, 80);
					options.Listen(IPAddress.Any, 443,
				   listenOptions =>
						{
							try
							{
								listenOptions.NoDelay = true;
								listenOptions.UseHttps("wildcard_obsidianplatform_com.pfx", args[0]); // hk
								listenOptions.UseConnectionLogging();
							}
							catch (Exception) { }
						});
					options.UseSystemd();
```
On Windows, that works as expected:
Now listening on: http://0.0.0.0:80
Now listening on: https://0.0.0.0:443

But the same on Ubuntu yields http instead of http on port 443:
Now listening on: http://0.0.0.0:80
Now listening on: http://0.0.0.0:443

The result is that on Ubuntu port 443 will not serve https but http, which is of course not what I want.

Any ideas?

